<section class="card">
  <h2>About Sweet Corn</h2>

  <p>
    Sweet corn (Zea mays var. saccharata) is a warm-season annual grown for fresh ears.
    It is <strong>frost-sensitive</strong> and performs best when planted into warming soil.
  </p>

  <p>
    In short growing seasons, success depends on two things:
    planting after soil warms and selecting early-maturing varieties.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Temperature & Soil Requirements</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Germination minimum:</strong> ~50°F (10°C) (slow and uneven)</li>
    <li><strong>Better germination:</strong> 60–65°F (16–18°C) soil temperature</li>
    <li><strong>Optimal growth:</strong> 70–86°F (21–30°C)</li>
    <li><strong>Frost damage:</strong> 32°F (0°C) and below</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Early planting into cold soil often results in poor stands and delayed maturity.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Planting Window</h2>

  <p>
    Sweet corn is usually <strong>direct sown</strong> after your average last spring frost,
    once soil has warmed and the forecast is stable.
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>Plant in blocks rather than long single rows to improve pollination.</li>
    <li>Stagger plantings only if your season length supports it.</li>
  </ul>

  <p class="fine muted" style="margin-top:14px;">
    If nights remain cold, waiting a week often produces a better stand than planting early.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Variety Selection for Short Seasons</h2>

  <p>
    Days-to-maturity varies widely. In colder climates, prioritize <strong>early</strong> sweet corn.
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Early varieties:</strong> often 60–75 days</li>
    <li><strong>Midseason:</strong> often 75–90 days</li>
    <li><strong>Late:</strong> often 90+ days (higher risk in short seasons)</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    If your first fall frost arrives early, late varieties may not fully size or sweeten.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Pollination Notes</h2>

  <p>
    Corn is wind-pollinated. Poor pollination causes missing kernels and uneven ear fill.
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>Plant in at least a 4×4 block when possible.</li>
    <li>Avoid planting far apart from nearby corn types that could cross-pollinate.</li>
    <li>Hot, dry winds during tasseling can reduce pollination success.</li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Fall Frost Considerations</h2>

  <p>
    Sweet corn plants are damaged by frost. If frost is approaching:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>Harvest mature ears promptly.</li>
    <li>Immature ears may not improve after frost.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    In short-season regions, planting date + early variety selection are the main tools for managing frost risk.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

  <details>
    <summary>Can sweet corn survive a light frost?</summary>
    <p>
      No. Sweet corn foliage is frost-sensitive, and a freeze can severely damage plants and reduce yield.
    </p>
  </details>

  <details>
    <summary>Is it worth planting corn early to gain time?</summary>
    <p>
      Usually not. Cold soil delays emergence and can cost more time than you gain.
      Plant once soil is warm enough for fast, even germination.
    </p>
  </details>

  <details>
    <summary>Why plant corn in blocks?</summary>
    <p>
      Corn is wind-pollinated. Blocks improve pollen coverage and lead to better kernel fill.
    </p>
  </details>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Summary</h2>

  <ol>
    <li>Sweet corn is a warm-season crop and is killed by frost.</li>
    <li>Direct sow after last frost once soil warms for reliable germination.</li>
    <li>Choose early varieties for short growing seasons.</li>
    <li>Plant in blocks to improve pollination and ear fill.</li>
  </ol>
</section>
